            <entry xml:id="entry_dyzærdyg" xml:lang="os">
                <form xml:lang="os-x-iron" type="lemma"><orth>dyzærdyg</orth></form>
                <form xml:lang="os-x-digor" type="dialectal"><orth>duzærdug</orth></form>
                <sense><sense><abv:tr xml:lang="ru">
                            <q>сомнение</q>
                        </abv:tr><abv:tr xml:lang="en">
                            <q>doubt</q>
                        </abv:tr></sense><sense><abv:tr xml:lang="ru">
                            <q>колебание</q>
                        </abv:tr><abv:tr xml:lang="en">
                            <q>hesitation</q>
                        </abv:tr></sense><sense><abv:tr xml:lang="ru">
                            <q>сомневающийся</q>
                        </abv:tr><abv:tr xml:lang="en">
                            <q>doubtful</q>
                        </abv:tr></sense><sense><abv:tr xml:lang="ru">
                            <q>колеблющийся</q>
                        </abv:tr><abv:tr xml:lang="en">
                            <q>hesitating</q>
                        </abv:tr></sense></sense>
                <etym xml:lang="ru">Буквально „двусердие“; см. <ref type="xr" target="#entry_dy-"/>
                    | %idu%i и <ref type="xr" target="#entry_zærdæ"/> ‘сердце’. Ср. <mentioned
                        xml:lang="fa"><lang/>
                        <w>dödil</w>
                        <gloss><q>сомневающийся</q></gloss></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="fa"><w/>
                        <gloss><q>колеблющийся</q></gloss></mentioned>, буквально „двусердый“. Такое
                    же образование, но с иным значением, в грузинском: <mentioned xml:lang="ka"><lang/>
                        <w>orguli</w>
                        <gloss><q>вероломный</q></gloss></mentioned> из <mentioned xml:lang="ka"><lang/>
                        <w>ori</w>
                        <gloss><q>два</q></gloss></mentioned> и <mentioned xml:lang="ka"><lang/>
                        <w>guli</w>
                        <gloss><q>сердце</q></gloss></mentioned>. — Ср. <ref type="xr"
                        target="#entry_īwzærdyg"/>.%n<bibl><ref type="bibl"
                            target="#ref_Вс._Миллер._Gr."/><biblScope>48,
                    90</biblScope></bibl>.</etym>
                <etym xml:lang="en">Literally “double-heartness”; see <ref type="xr"
                        target="#entry_dy-"/> | %idu%i and <ref type="xr" target="#entry_zærdæ"/>
                    ‘heary’. Ср. <mentioned xml:lang="fa"><lang/>
                        <w>dödil</w>
                        <gloss><q>doubtful</q></gloss></mentioned>, <mentioned xml:lang="fa"><w/>
                        <gloss><q>hesitating</q></gloss></mentioned>, literally “two hearted”. The
                    same derivative but with another meaning is found in Georgian: <mentioned
                        xml:lang="ka"><lang/>
                        <w>orguli</w>
                        <gloss><q>faithless</q></gloss></mentioned> from <mentioned xml:lang="ka"><lang/>
                        <w>ori</w>
                        <gloss><q>two</q></gloss></mentioned> and <mentioned xml:lang="ka"><lang/>
                        <w>guli</w>
                        <gloss><q>heart</q></gloss></mentioned>. — Cf. <ref type="xr"
                        target="#entry_īwzærdyg"/>.%n<bibl><ref type="bibl"
                            target="#ref_Вс._Миллер._Gr."/><biblScope>48,
                    90</biblScope></bibl>.</etym>
            </entry>
